Briquette was very convenient during my last visit to New Orleans, but I agree with other reviewers - I don’t recommend having dinner there. The food was okay. I’d compare the entrée I had to something that would be served at the Cheesecake Factory, only more expensive. Nothing special and I certainly wasn’t “wow’d.” The pasta was a huge portion (way too much, in my opinion). Portion size doesn’t make up for mediocracy. Everything but the salad dressing was under-seasoned and it would’ve been nice if they served a piece of crusty baguette with the Briquette salad since there is a big dollop of goat cheese on the side by itself. The drinks were decent when we finally received them. The service was awful. This is not the place to bring clients that you’re trying to impress. It seemed to me that they are grossly understaffed. It took almost 10 minutes for someone to realize we walked in the door at the time of our reservation (only about 25% of tables were occupied). The amount of time that it took to order drinks was excessive, and the order wasn’t even correct the first time. The dining room is beautiful (and huge by New Orleans standards). There is so much potential, but food and service are very underwhelming. For the same price (maybe even a little less) and better service,you’re much better-off going to Cochon or Peche.

One detractor was a waiter that showed up after we were seated and eating.  He was distractingly loud and course of language & actions.  However, all things taken into account, our experience was 4.5 stars almost a 5 star.  One Year Ago... Briquette has amazing food and service!  We went there for our family thanksgiving meal and were so impressed.  We generally eat big family meals at home because we all love to cook and are all foodies, so eating out can be difficult.  But Briquette was a great experience on every level.  The service was incredible- we had 6 adults and two small children.  Some waiters can be impatient with kids but Elizabeth was on top of every need they had.  She also had the kitchen prepare a plate of buttered noodles for them which was so appreciated.  Our meal was delicious and perfectly prepared.  The house salad was delicious, the oysters and Brussels sprouts were all on point.  The blackened redfish was the best I have ever tasted, as well as the snapper, lamb shank and chicken Marsala.  Even the fettuccine Alfredo that came with the Marsala was divine.   We would have loved to have tried the dessert, but the portions are generous so no room!  (Not complaining- we loved every bite).  We will de definitely return, and sing their praises to all of our friends.  Thanks so much for a memorable thanksgiving dinner.

This place was absolutely awesome! The food was perfectly done. Flavor, balance, presentation. All were done with the customers satisfaction in mind. We got there just after the doors opened around 5:15pm on a Saturday. There were a few people there, but plenty of open seats. We were given a tour of the kitchen area and not only shown the fresh fish on display, but also educated on them as well. We got to meet all the chefs including the executive chef. The whole experience just felt welcoming. Our waiter Darrell was incredibly attentive and personable. Anything we may have needed was addressed immediately. Although Briquette is a higher priced dining experience, I feel that based on the quality of food and service received, it was worth it. My only regret is that I should have worn a polo shirt. Not that anyone said or alluded to it, but I felt I should have dressed more business casual. Regardless, my wife and I had a great time and left full and happy. Our food that we ordered was: Caramelized Sea Scallops with a delicious fried goat cheese grit base (my favorite), Louisiana Redfish on the Half Shell, and Snapper Pontchartrain (which was our favorite entree). You can't go wrong with any of those items. Well done Briquette!

This was a highly anticipated dinner that had been planned for months in advance with friends and family only to turn out to be a big dissapointment. I do have to say that the service and atmosphere were excellent but, the food.... terrible. For our appetizer we order the scallops on goat cheese grit cake. The scallops were okay and the grit cake had no goat cheese flavor and was hard as a brick. For the mains we ordered the visiting fish (triple tail) and the ribeye steak medium rare. Well, the fish was covered in a sauce that was greasy and unappetizing. The fish itself was undercooked and flavorless. Some old guy came over to the table (I assume he was the manager) and asked how it was and we told him about it. So, he grabbed the silverware and started cutting into the fish saying,"you'd enjoy it more if you knew how to eat it" and proceeded to shred the fish to pieces??? Weird and demeaning experience. I am from Florida. I know how to eat fish! Anyways, the steak was medium well to well and was supposed to be garlic and rosemary crusted. NOPE! Tasted like a boiled steak. Terrible. They offered to precook it but honestly I was so turned off by this point I didn't want to wait another hour for another flavorless steak. They offered dessert instead but we declined. Then they offered to take my one glass of wine off the bill. Which they didn't! How about you take the whole dinner off since we didn't eat it? $164.00 later (not including the tip) we went home and I got sick. Fabulous. This was the WORST dining experience I have ever had.

Been waiting for months to eat here on our trip to New Orleans.  First in counter was not good. The gentleman that opens the door for everyone, everyone except us, coming to and leaving came up to my brother in law and said to take his hat off. He came out of nowhere on the street and we didn't know he even worked there...he was rude about it.  We ordered the Caramelized Sea Scallops, Steamed Prince Edward Mussels, Lump Crab Bisque, and Ahi Poke for starters.  The ONLY good thing out of those were the mussels...even though there were 4 bad tasting ones. The sea scallops were foul I had to walk to the bathroom to spit it out. Crab bisque was not good...it was bright yellow I assume from curry and tasted so bad. For our meals were Speckled Trout Almondine, Pork Porterhouse, and the District Tournedos. The Pork porterhouse was supposed to be cooked medium it was way overcooked...hard and dry. Our other entrees at the table were good. The District Tournedos were delicious and cooked to oerfection as well as the trout almondine. I also ordered a mixed drink of the specialties menu supposed to be coconut, melon, lime, and oj. But instead it tasted like a 12.00 Screwdriver. Had family at next table. Both the meals were horrible they got the Visiting Market Whole fish and the Ribeye. The triple tail whole fish had a very fishy oily taste. The ribeye was supposed to be medium and was far beyond medium past even well. The only star was Daniel our waiter I felt so bad we had to complain to him none of this was his fault. Sad that I had looked forward to this meal and that it is a beautiful space and the experience is horrible. Now we leave town tomorrow and this is the experience we end our trip with...

To begin, there's a drink/wine list lying around on every table. When I saw that, I kind of figured they get it. A palatable wine list for both the novice and connoisseur at one's fingertips before the conversation ever begins. To the food...The turtle soup that my husband ordered was so good that I forgot to take a pic. However I did get snaps of his redfish (pan fried to perfection) and my duck.  You won't find a bone in-skin intact duck shank anywhere else to my knowledge. Look at the photo...the skin is crispy and flavorful. Meat is moist and not too gamey. Side note...I could've made a meal of the Swiss chard and pork belly plantain mash that were three sides of the dish. Everything about dinner was completely satisfying and left us full. But then....  I had to ask about dessert. Of course. And so,  the pies de resistance was the "floating island" meringue cake. To clarify, this is not a cake made of batter. It is a finely and acutely rendered meringue confection that looks exactly like a piece of cake, but it's all meringue, so it completely melts in your mouth. Be sure to add a piece of the housemade caramel crackle candy and anglaise to each bite. It is rare to find this delicacy, even in France. My mom used to say there's always room for jello. Well, jello feels like concrete compared to the island. JUST. GET. IT. With a glass of prosecco, of course! ;-)  Kat (or maybe Cat), our server, was always on time without encroaching. Visiting with GM Nic was a treat. You can tell that he holds his title, and the responsibilities that come with it, close to his chest. Hopefully you'll get the chance to visit with him a bit and hear a story.

Had the best grilled.snapper...Toby at the bar was AWESOME....Darrell  our server was the best..Friendly,  attentive... great atmosphere. One of the best  Happy Hours I've been to... Great night at a really great restaurant..We will.return!!!!

We enjoyed our time at Briquette, our server Tess was very welcoming and attentive. The shrimp po-boy with fried green tomato was the best thing ever, so were the fries. Chocolate creme brûlée was great too though on a heavy, chocolate-mousse side.  The negative experience came unexpectedly, when I had to suppress a gag reflex when trying to eat the mussels. They smelled a bit...”poop-y”. Mussels have to be stored in proper drainage and then rinsed before being served, otherwise they end up marinating in their own excrement.  We let Tess know the mussels weren’t safe to eat, we haven’t touched them but did consume all the fries on the bottom (which were sooo good).  We saw Tess dutifully informing chef. We saw the same mussels being served to other table. We then saw mussels on our bill.  Spoiled shellfish is no-joke, someone could get very sick. Making someone pay for spoiled food they didn’t eat?.. come on, chef of Briquette, no way your restaurant is doing that bad.

Large, upscale restaurant with good food. Large business clientele for weekday lunch. Weekends can be difficult to get in without a reservation. The Ahi with roast potatoes and green beans was excellent. The blackened shrimp cajun pasta was good, but not to my taste. The macaroni looked like vesuvio, a thick, short corkscrew pasta. Not good with the sauce. And the sauce was more like a broth thickened with corn starch than it was a cream sauce. The shrimp certainly wasn't blackened. It had spinach and mushrooms. So it was fancy and different and I know many people would like it. But not me. I added a ton of cajun seasoning and salt.  Service was slow. In fairness, there were 8 tables handled by 1 waiter, but the place looked empty. 3 singles, 3 couples a table of 5 and a table of 6. Had to keep asking for things the waiter forgot when asked (like cajun spice). Worth going to though and they change the menu. So what you see online probably won't be what they are serving when you go.

She toppled a tray of drinks,  breaking glass all over the tray. She served the remaining drinks,  so we sent them back because there was no way to know if broken glass was in the drinks. After that, service went way downhill. At the end, she kept saying we hadn't paid enough, but we had, she just wasn't entering it correctly in the system. She came back three times accusing us of underpaying. We kept adding it up for her. Finally we had to call the manager. They finally figured out that she wasn't pushing a button on the register to add one of the cards (which had been ran, so payment was made). It was really ridiculous. This was a bad end to an otherwise nice meal. The bar menu was not great, and er didn't love the drinks, but the food was really good. It's a shame the service ruined it.
